<br>
     I have seen your posts on other boards and I usually agree with what you have to say. But as you say, you do not play on FV and are only looking at it from the outside, so you what not really know what is going on. Even looking at posts will not help you much as people will post bad experiences a lot quicker than good. You would have to play here to know. Now my rebuttal.<br>
<br>
&lt;&lt;and the forced anon making LFG pretty useless&gt;&gt;<br>
<br>
I see this as a good thing as it makes you interact with other players.<br>
<br>
&lt;&lt;and the grouping restrictions, it just seems like it would be a nightmare to get groups.&gt;&gt;<br>
<br>
The only real group restriction is good cannot group with evil, that is just good roleplaying to me. <br>
<br>
&lt;&lt;The rules are the rules. I still don't see how any of them promote roleplaying at all. Mostly they just seem to introduce more frustration into a game that already has a lot of frustration elements. Languages may be a RP thing, but that seems like something to be powergamed over -- and I see suggestions on making learning multiple languages a priority. If that's the solution, what's the point anyway? Tho I suppose this would be a harmless enough rule to keep the d00dieheads off the server.&gt;&gt;<br>
<br>
Lets take all this at once. The rules do work. TLC keeps the 50 somethings from blowing thru a zone my 25th level cleric's is patiently trying to work our way to a mob that has the magic item we would like but that the 50th level character just walks up to and takes. The language barrier makes you make friends with others of your same race first, then later others of different races. Yes, but if you are power learning languages, why come to a RP server?<br>
<br>
&lt;&lt;If they got rid of the stupid RP/anon tag, which serves no purpose other than to force people to ask OOC questions and make it harder to find groups, that would actually do a lot to make me think it was a viable server.&gt;&gt;<br>
<br>
If you are roleplaying why would you want to automatically know what level and class everyone on the server is? And it does not force you to ask OOC questions at all.<br>
<br>
     I actually see all of this as an improvement, on what other server do see a group take whatever class that walks up, instead of waiting to get that perfect mix. On my old server, you never saw a group with 4 clerics and a caster or 2. Or a group of all melee. Everybody wanted balanced groups. I love this server, it is friendly, like a small town where everybody knows everyone else. The only reason that you cannot find groups is if you are the anti-social type. If you are that type, play a druid or necro. I can walk in to any zone in my level range and if there is a group there, I walk up to them and if the group is not full voila, I am invited. They do not even ask what class until I am in the group. Sure it is small, but it is new and growing and I have seen it move up (or down) in the population lists lately meaning that it is getting bigger. The only problem I see is that there are alot of power gamers who leveled to 50+ very quick and now are wondering why alot more people did not level almost as quickly as they were accustomed to on blue servers.<br>
<br>
Lexxi Ledenyetz<br>
25th Prayer<br>
Cleric of Brell<br>
Ak'Anon<br>
